Elizabeth is a healthy
premature baby--

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:16.300
her lungs actively
suck in the air;

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:18.460
her heart beats on its own.

00:06:18.460 --> 00:06:21.800
But the one organ central
to all the others

00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:24.430
is not fully prepared--
her brain.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:29.960
The miracle technologies
of modern medicine

00:06:29.960 --> 00:06:31.930
can help keep Elizabeth alive

00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:34.900
but 12 critical weeks
of brain development

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:39.260
must now continue outside the
protective walls of the womb.

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:44.830
WOMAN:
When the baby comes out of
the womb, everything changes--

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:48.560
suddenly light,
suddenly sharp sounds.

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:53.230
The brain reacts
to the stimulation.

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:58.060
It can't filter, it can't stop,
it can't shut it out.

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:05.160
They survive
and make the best of it.

00:07:05.160 --> 00:07:07.160
Yet what's the cost?

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:16.400
NARRATOR:
The brain of a baby born three
months premature is vulnerable.

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:19.960
Many precious weeks
of development still remain.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:28.600
Billions of brain cells
are not done forging links

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:30.960
with billions
of other brain cells.

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:38.830
Eventually, there will be
trillions and trillions

00:07:38.830 --> 00:07:40.730
of connections between cells

00:07:40.730 --> 00:07:42.760
charged with electrical pulses

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:46.700
rippling like lightning storms
across the hills and valleys

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:49.230
of the brain's
deeply furrowed tissue.

00:07:54.330 --> 00:07:56.400
Every cell in its place,

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:00.230
every link between cells
carefully organized--

00:08:00.230 --> 00:08:03.760
nothing random,
nothing arbitrary.

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:07.360
WOMAN:
What we would really love
to understand

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:10.230
is how the brain,
during development,

00:08:10.230 --> 00:08:13.460
generates millions and millions
of neurons,

00:08:13.460 --> 00:08:16.930
sends them to the right position
in the brain,

00:08:16.930 --> 00:08:22.600
and then somehow instructs each
of those individual nerve cells

00:08:22.600 --> 00:08:27.760
to form very, very specific
connections with one another.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:30.630
You can think about development
like a play--

00:08:30.630 --> 00:08:32.460
a play that follows a script

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:35.030
that is written down
by the genetic code

00:08:35.030 --> 00:08:38.030
but it has no director,
it has no producer

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:40.100
and it has a bunch of actors

00:08:40.100 --> 00:08:43.130
that have never spoken
their lines before.

00:08:43.130 --> 00:08:46.000
Despite all this,
you pull the play off.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.800
To me, that's a miracle.

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:57.560
NARRATOR:
Egg and sperm-- their union
forms a single cell

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:01.660
which will divide, and divide,
and divide again.

00:09:07.530 --> 00:09:10.400
Within three weeks,
the multiplying cells

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:13.130
have curled into
a quivering oval ball.

00:09:16.300 --> 00:09:18.700
Inside lies a cluster of cells

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:21.360
that have begun
to fold themselves

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:25.230
into the shape of a garden hose,
the neural tube.

00:09:28.100 --> 00:09:32.660
From the bottom will come
the spinal cord;

00:09:32.660 --> 00:09:35.360
from the top, the brain.

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:38.160
Here lies
the primitive beginning

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:41.000
of all our thoughts
and feelings.

00:09:44.230 --> 00:09:48.700
By four weeks, just as a woman
is discovering she is pregnant

00:09:48.700 --> 00:09:51.230
the first brain cells,
the neurons,

00:09:51.230 --> 00:09:55.660
are already forming
at an astonishing rate--

00:09:55.660 --> 00:09:58.100
500,000 neurons every minute--

00:09:58.100 --> 00:10:01.630
neurons that will never
reproduce themselves

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:04.500
and rarely be replaced.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:07.430
McCONNELL:
And that's amazing,
because if you think about it

00:10:07.430 --> 00:10:09.330
most cells in your body
turn over.

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:12.160
If you think about your skin,
you're constantly...

00:10:12.160 --> 00:10:13.630
it's sort of disgusting--

00:10:13.630 --> 00:10:16.300
you're constantly sloughing off
dead skin cells.

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:18.360
And someone calculated once

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:22.730
that if you look at the turnover
of skin across a lifetime

00:10:22.730 --> 00:10:25.630
you're probably generating
and shedding

00:10:25.630 --> 00:10:27.500
about 90 pounds of skin.

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:30.760
So, most cells in the body
do their thing

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:34.000
and then they die,
and they're replaced.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.330
Neurons are born in fetal life

00:10:36.330 --> 00:10:39.230
and then those very cells
are the ones

00:10:39.230 --> 00:10:43.260
that are still functioning
all the way into old age.

00:10:48.100 --> 00:10:50.360
NARRATOR:
As the tiny fetus grows

00:10:50.360 --> 00:10:54.430
the neurons make their way out
from inside the neural tube

00:10:54.430 --> 00:10:58.100
to build the brain, layer
upon layer, like an onion.

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:04.060
The neurons follow
a cellular pathway

00:11:04.060 --> 00:11:07.030
as if they were traveling
down a highway.

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:10.700
They just grab hold of
supporting cells called "glia"

00:11:10.700 --> 00:11:13.930
and propel themselves along.

00:11:13.930 --> 00:11:16.600
WOMAN:
They put their nucleus
in the back of the cell

00:11:16.600 --> 00:11:18.660
which makes them sort of fat
in the back

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:21.700
and then they hold on to the
guide wire, this glial fiber.

00:11:24.230 --> 00:11:26.930
So, it's kind of like an
inchworm as it moves along.

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:31.460
And each little cell
goes all by itself

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:35.060
in what is a very,
very vulnerable process.

00:11:35.060 --> 00:11:37.500
No other kind of cell
has to do that

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:39.700
and it's just an amazing thing.

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:44.660
NARRATOR:
Neurons travel in waves--

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:48.960
millions every day embarking
on a daunting expedition

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:51.560
that scientists call migration.

00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:53.230
WOMAN:
It's an amazing phenomenon

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:56.000
because it's as if they are
going across the country.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.730
I mean, in terms of the
distances relative to their size

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:02.430
they're... they're making
a huge odyssey

00:12:02.430 --> 00:12:05.030
through all kinds
of foreign territory.

00:12:05.030 --> 00:12:07.730
And the most amazing thing
about this migration

00:12:07.730 --> 00:12:10.400
is that they generally do it
without mistakes.

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:12.400
They're following cues
along the way

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:14.760
that are telling them
exactly where to go.

00:12:16.360 --> 00:12:18.960
NARRATOR:
For years, scientists wondered

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:22.630
how the migrating neurons
find their place in the brain.

00:12:22.630 --> 00:12:25.200
Do the neurons simply travel
in herds

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:27.160
gliding down a glial highway

00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:30.260
which takes them
to their final destination?

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:33.260
Or do neurons
do their own driving,

00:12:33.260 --> 00:12:36.230
each neuron
genetically programmed

00:12:36.230 --> 00:12:39.800
to fulfill its own
predetermined purpose?

00:12:39.800 --> 00:12:42.530
McCONNELL:
We used to think that migration

00:12:42.530 --> 00:12:45.830
was just like delivering cells
out a conveyor belt

00:12:45.830 --> 00:12:48.830
and we just dump out the cells
at the end.

00:12:48.830 --> 00:12:51.430
But now we know
that's not the case.

00:12:51.430 --> 00:12:56.130
There is evidence that shows
that young neurons

00:12:56.130 --> 00:13:00.700
have an idea about
where they're migrating to

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:04.530
and that they can recognize
their position within the brain.

00:13:08.130 --> 00:13:11.360
NARRATOR:
In her laboratory
at Stanford University

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:15.500
neurobiologist Susan McConnell
devised a series of experiments

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:18.360
to track the destiny
of a migrating neuron.

00:13:19.900 --> 00:13:23.260
Neurons are born from
the division of stem cells

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:26.760
the seeds from which
the tissues of the body grow.

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:29.560
Some stem cells
can transform themselves

00:13:29.560 --> 00:13:31.230
into any kind of cell--

00:13:31.230 --> 00:13:35.960
blood, skin, heart, bone...
or brain cell.

00:13:38.100 --> 00:13:40.400
McConnell took a descendant
of a stem cell

00:13:40.400 --> 00:13:42.360
and before it morphed
into a neuron

00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:46.000
transplanted it
into a developing brain;

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.360
then, watched it migrate.

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:57.460
She found that the fate
of the soon-to-become neuron

00:13:57.460 --> 00:14:01.100
was determined by the neurons
that were its neighbors.

00:14:01.100 --> 00:14:06.100
It traveled beside them and took
on the same function they did.

00:14:06.100 --> 00:14:07.800
McCONNELL:
That cell is plastic;

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:10.460
it's still listening to signals
from the outside.

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:13.030
It gets the instructions
from the new neighbors

00:14:13.030 --> 00:14:14.330
and it resets its fate.

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:16.600
It says, "Yeah, sure,
I can do that, too."

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:21.160
NARRATOR:
But when McConnell
transplanted a neuron

00:14:21.160 --> 00:14:23.630
it was true to
its own genetic destiny--

00:14:23.630 --> 00:14:25.430
it followed its own path

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:28.560
and took on an entirely
different function

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:30.860
from the cells surrounding it.

00:14:30.860 --> 00:14:33.530
McCONNELL:
What this result tells us

00:14:33.530 --> 00:14:37.700
is that by the time a young
neuron begins its migration

00:14:37.700 --> 00:14:40.460
it has already
received instructions

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:42.160
about what to become;

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:43.230
it knows.

00:14:43.230 --> 00:14:44.760
It goes into a new environment

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:47.060
and even though everyone else
in the brain...

00:14:47.060 --> 00:14:49.800
All these other young neurons
are going to position A

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:52.330
it says, "No, no, I'm supposed
to go to position B"

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:54.000
and that's exactly what it does.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:58.530
(<i> fetus's heart beating</i> )

00:14:58.530 --> 00:15:03.900
NARRATOR:
By 24 weeks, the vital organs
of the fetus are well formed;

00:15:03.900 --> 00:15:06.600
the primitive heart
can beat on its own,

00:15:06.600 --> 00:15:08.860
the once powerless lungs

00:15:08.860 --> 00:15:11.100
are now prepared
to fill with air

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:14.100
and the brain has
nearly its full compliment

00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:16.500
of billions and billions
of neurons

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:18.600
reaching out to each other,

00:15:18.600 --> 00:15:22.060
building connections
with mind-boggling speed,

00:15:22.060 --> 00:15:24.430
nearly two million
every second,

00:15:24.430 --> 00:15:28.300
until the brain has become
a tightly packed network

00:15:28.300 --> 00:15:30.960
of trillions
of crisscrossing wires

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:34.330
with more connections
than stars in the sky.

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:42.000
SHATZ:
You can imagine the size
of the wiring problem.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.400
So, how's that problem solved?

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:46.500
How is that achieved
during development?

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:49.130
How is that each one of those
trillion connections

00:15:49.130 --> 00:15:50.760
is made appropriately?

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:52.260
You might think,
"Oh, what a mess.

00:15:52.260 --> 00:15:54.730
It's just going to be a jumble
of connections and wires

00:15:54.730 --> 00:15:56.230
all over the place."

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:59.930
But in fact, the nervous system
seems to have a strategy.

00:16:02.400 --> 00:16:05.430
NARRATOR:
The strategy is in the genes.

00:16:05.430 --> 00:16:07.900
The brain begins to wire itself

00:16:07.900 --> 00:16:12.100
by following a precisely
specified genetic blueprint.

00:16:12.100 --> 00:16:17.000
SHATZ:
The connections are following
very defined rules.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:21.630
You know, "Go out of the eye,
turn right at the optic chiasm,

00:16:21.630 --> 00:16:26.300
cross the chiasm, head toward
the lateral geniculate nucleus,

00:16:26.300 --> 00:16:28.500
grow into
the lateral geniculate nucleus.

00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:31.000
Don't grow into the medial
geniculate nucleus

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.060
because that's
an auditory structure.

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:35.900
So you can imagine the first
stage of brain wiring

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:37.900
is kind of like solving
the problem

00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:40.930
of connecting phones in New York
to phones in Boston;

00:16:40.930 --> 00:16:43.560
making sure that
you're making connections

00:16:43.560 --> 00:16:47.600
between Boston and New York and
not Boston and Washington, D.C.

00:16:47.600 --> 00:16:49.960
And that's all specified
genetically.

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:54.530
Now then, there's a second phase
of brain wiring.

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:56.800
Let's say you want
to place a phone call

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:00.560
to your grandmother in New York,
and you want<i> that</i> phone to ring,

00:17:00.560 --> 00:17:03.260
you know, on Park Avenue
and 47th, or wherever,

00:17:03.260 --> 00:17:07.700
and you don't want the phone to
ring up at the Waldorf Astoria.

00:17:07.700 --> 00:17:11.100
Okay, how do you get
that precise phone to ring?

00:17:11.100 --> 00:17:13.960
That's the second phase
of brain wiring.

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:16.730
If you place a phone call
to your grandmother

00:17:16.730 --> 00:17:18.800
early in development...

00:17:23.260 --> 00:17:25.260
Her phone will ring...

00:17:29.360 --> 00:17:33.330
But so will
a lot of other phones.

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:36.400
So there are a lot of
connections that are made.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:39.360
If the connections are correct
and being used,

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:41.460
they get strengthened.

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:43.430
If they're not being used

00:17:43.430 --> 00:17:47.130
or if they're only being used
occasionally, they're lost.

00:17:47.130 --> 00:17:49.860
We could call it
"use it or lose it."

00:17:53.230 --> 00:17:56.260
So the fetal brain is really
a dynamic structure

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:59.700
that's constantly changing
in response to this process

00:17:59.700 --> 00:18:02.330
of strengthening
appropriate connections

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:04.930
and pruning
inappropriate connections.

00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:11.460
Getting the circuits
all tuned up takes a long time

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:15.060
so it can't happen overnight

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:18.800
because you have literally
billions of connections
to check.

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:20.800
(<i> fetus's heart beating</i> )

00:18:30.030 --> 00:18:32.500
When a child
is born prematurely,

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:34.960
the process is only partly over.

00:18:39.700 --> 00:18:42.330
So a huge amount of brain wiring

00:18:42.330 --> 00:18:45.130
is having to happen
in the nursery.

00:18:50.460 --> 00:18:55.560
(<i> monitor beeping</i> )

00:19:04.730 --> 00:19:08.000
NARRATOR:
At Brigham and Women's Hospital
in Boston,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:12.000
