(<i> continuing to shush</i> )

00:26:39.930 --> 00:26:43.360
NARRATOR:
She'll be going back
to see Dr. Als in two months...

00:26:45.300 --> 00:26:48.800
Just after she was supposed
to have been born.

00:26:52.700 --> 00:26:55.430
Als wants to compare
Elizabeth's brain

00:26:55.430 --> 00:26:58.360
to the brains
of other premature babies,

00:26:58.360 --> 00:27:01.930
premies who spent
the first days of their lives

00:27:01.930 --> 00:27:05.100
in a standard hospital
intensive care unit.

00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:08.560
Will the special treatment
Elizabeth received

00:27:08.560 --> 00:27:11.000
make a difference?

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.460
How much influence
does the world around us have

00:27:13.460 --> 00:27:15.230
on the developing brain?

00:27:27.500 --> 00:27:29.760
To help answer that question,

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:32.860
neuroscientists turned
to a small animal

00:27:32.860 --> 00:27:36.430
immortalized in a portrait
by Leonardo Da Vinci

00:27:36.430 --> 00:27:40.730
over 500 years ago...
the ferret.

00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:45.830
MAN:
The most fundamental question

00:27:45.830 --> 00:27:48.100
in understanding
how the brain develops

00:27:48.100 --> 00:27:51.260
has to be the interaction
between nature and nurture.

00:27:59.300 --> 00:28:02.430
We know that
the brain has different areas

00:28:02.430 --> 00:28:04.860
that do different things,

00:28:04.860 --> 00:28:08.800
such as the visual cortex
at the back of the brain...

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:13.000
or the auditory cortex
in the middle of the brain.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:16.060
How do these areas
get to be where they are

00:28:16.060 --> 00:28:20.030
and how do they do what
they end up doing in the adult?

00:28:22.630 --> 00:28:26.300
NARRATOR:
How plastic is the brain,
how flexible?

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:29.260
Can nurture trump
what nature intended?

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.330
In a series
of elegant experiments,

00:28:33.330 --> 00:28:35.560
neuroscientist Mriganka Sur

00:28:35.560 --> 00:28:38.500
restructured the brains
of newborn ferrets.

00:28:44.060 --> 00:28:46.430
In the normal ferret,

00:28:46.430 --> 00:28:49.860
light striking the eye
creates electrical waves

00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:52.260
that travel
to the visual cortex.

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:54.830
Sur rewired the ferret's brain,

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:58.360
hooking up the eyes
to the auditory cortex,

00:28:58.360 --> 00:29:01.230
showering the hearing parts
of the brain

00:29:01.230 --> 00:29:04.300
with electric waves
generated by the light.

00:29:04.300 --> 00:29:10.100
SUR:
We reasoned that if we can make
visual inputs from the eye

00:29:10.100 --> 00:29:15.530
go to the auditory cortex
that normally processes hearing,

00:29:15.530 --> 00:29:20.060
would the hearing cortex
now become like a visual cortex

00:29:20.060 --> 00:29:22.600
or a seeing cortex

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:26.830
if it grew up with vision
rather than with audition?

00:29:26.830 --> 00:29:29.630
Would the hearing cortex
now come to have

00:29:29.630 --> 00:29:31.860
the same circuits
and connections

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:33.860
that mark the visual cortex?

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:37.900
If it doesn't, then nature,
or the genetic endowment,

00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:39.900
is of the essence.

00:29:39.900 --> 00:29:43.100
If it does, then
the inputs are important,

00:29:43.100 --> 00:29:46.930
or nurture is important,
and the animal would see.

00:29:50.030 --> 00:29:52.530
NARRATOR:
By recording a series of images

00:29:52.530 --> 00:29:55.600
directly from the brains
of his rewired ferrets,

00:29:55.600 --> 00:29:59.000
Sur provided evidence
that the ferrets could see.

00:30:01.760 --> 00:30:03.160
With normal ferrets,

00:30:03.160 --> 00:30:06.400
the activity of the neurons
in the visual cortex

00:30:06.400 --> 00:30:09.160
takes on a characteristic
pinwheel shape.

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:14.300
With the rewired ferrets,

00:30:14.300 --> 00:30:18.930
the auditory cortex describes
a similar pinwheel design.

00:30:18.930 --> 00:30:23.000
The brain has been transformed,
but not entirely.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.400
SUR:
Instead of 20/20 vision,

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:27.860
they will have, let's say,
20/60 vision,

00:30:27.860 --> 00:30:29.900
meaning that they see at 20 feet

00:30:29.900 --> 00:30:32.500
what a normal ferret
would see at 60 feet.

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:37.630
NARRATOR:
The characteristic pinwheel
is still there

00:30:37.630 --> 00:30:40.100
but it is less orderly.

00:30:40.100 --> 00:30:41.730
Slurred.

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:46.060
Environment shapes the brain

00:30:46.060 --> 00:30:50.160
but can't completely change
genetic destiny.

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:54.030
SUR:
Our experiments demonstrate
beautifully, I think,

00:30:54.030 --> 00:30:56.830
the interaction of nature
and nurture.

00:30:56.830 --> 00:31:02.600
I believe that the environment
writes on a developing brain

00:31:02.600 --> 00:31:06.060
but does not write
on a blank slate.

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:10.030
There is a structure
that comes about due to genes

00:31:10.030 --> 00:31:14.100
which then is influenced further
by the environment

00:31:14.100 --> 00:31:16.730
that the brain is developing in.

00:31:16.730 --> 00:31:19.630
Our experiments provide
very clear evidence

00:31:19.630 --> 00:31:22.460
of the remarkable plasticity
of the brain.

00:31:31.800 --> 00:31:35.730
NARRATOR:
Three weeks after the day she
