00:33:59.230 --> 00:34:01.500
That's very impressive,
yeah.

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:06.330
So overall, you've done
a remarkable job

00:34:06.330 --> 00:34:09.200
in supporting her,
yeah.

00:34:09.200 --> 00:34:13.830
It's not trivial,
a little baby, yeah.

00:34:22.930 --> 00:34:26.700
NARRATOR:
Elizabeth appeared
to be doing well.

00:34:26.700 --> 00:34:29.330
But she was enlisted
in another round of tests

00:34:29.330 --> 00:34:31.460
to learn if her behavior
corresponded

00:34:31.460 --> 00:34:35.060
to measurable changes
in her brain.

00:34:42.830 --> 00:34:45.100
DUFFY:
No one has really
done this before.

00:34:45.100 --> 00:34:48.700
It's only been recently
that we've had the experience

00:34:48.700 --> 00:34:50.000
to say, "Is it possible

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:52.600
"that our intervention
may actually be visible

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:55.100
"in terms of a change
in physical development

00:34:55.100 --> 00:34:56.330
of brain parameters?"

00:34:56.330 --> 00:35:01.600
Can we actually see it
in the brain?"

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:04.730
NARRATOR:
It's still too early
to draw conclusions.

00:35:06.900 --> 00:35:10.430
But we do know something
about Elizabeth.

00:35:10.430 --> 00:35:15.030
Pictures from the MRI
reveal normal brain maturation.

00:35:16.300 --> 00:35:19.160
And as for the results
of her EEG:

00:35:19.160 --> 00:35:20.830
DUFFY:
Oh, she's surpassed.

00:35:20.830 --> 00:35:23.700
Caught up, and surpassed
what I would expect.

00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:28.900
It's a very nice, normal,
exemplary full-term EEG

00:35:28.900 --> 00:35:32.660
that I could put in a textbook
as an example.

00:35:32.660 --> 00:35:35.730
"To what can we attribute this?"

00:35:35.730 --> 00:35:39.430
This will be the result
of our study.

00:35:39.430 --> 00:35:43.000
As scientists, we have
to be very cautious

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:46.330
not to overinterpret
individual cases.

00:35:46.330 --> 00:35:49.460
Uh, it's entirely possible
that her improvement

00:35:49.460 --> 00:35:52.000
was through her own
internal fortitude

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:55.900
and that we were bit players
in this... in this great game

00:35:55.900 --> 00:35:57.830
of growing up.

00:35:57.830 --> 00:36:00.430
On the other hand,
we might have been very crucial.

00:36:00.430 --> 00:36:03.260
And we'll never know, because
we can't wind the clock back

00:36:03.260 --> 00:36:05.000
and not do the intervention
on her.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.700
So what we have to do
is have a population

00:36:07.700 --> 00:36:11.760
where there is no intervention,
population with an intervention

00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:13.630
and compare them as a group.

00:36:13.630 --> 00:36:16.500
There will always be a star
in the nonintervened group

00:36:16.500 --> 00:36:19.430
who comes through well,
and there will always be someone

00:36:19.430 --> 00:36:21.360
that we...
we just couldn't help, uh,

00:36:21.360 --> 00:36:23.700
but on the average
is what we're looking for

00:36:23.700 --> 00:36:26.430
and that's what the scientific
method is all about.

00:36:26.430 --> 00:36:29.600
Elizabeth.

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:34.060
NARRATOR:
Whatever the reason, Elizabeth
is improving every day.

00:36:34.060 --> 00:36:35.230
Hi...

00:36:35.230 --> 00:36:36.960
How's my girl?

00:36:36.960 --> 00:36:39.400
NARRATOR:
And for her parents,
that's enough.

00:36:39.400 --> 00:36:41.600
MOTHER:
There's a great possibility

00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:45.030
for Elizabeth to have, uh,
normal brain development.

00:36:45.030 --> 00:36:46.960
(<i> cooing</i> )

00:36:46.960 --> 00:36:51.630
And that's just such
a huge gift.

00:36:51.630 --> 00:36:53.460
My hope when she was born was

00:36:53.460 --> 00:36:56.960
that by the time she reached
kindergarten age, people...

00:36:56.960 --> 00:36:59.630
she would just blend in
with her class, um,

00:36:59.630 --> 00:37:02.200
but there seems to be
a very good chance

00:37:02.200 --> 00:37:03.900
that on her first birthday,

00:37:03.900 --> 00:37:05.760
she will be starting
to toddle

00:37:05.760 --> 00:37:07.400
like any other
one-year-old

00:37:07.400 --> 00:37:09.400
and that...
that would be great.

00:37:23.930 --> 00:37:25.900
NARRATOR:
Premature or full-term,

00:37:25.900 --> 00:37:30.400
every baby is faced
with the same challenge.

00:37:30.400 --> 00:37:36.030
(<i> baby cooing</i> )

00:37:36.030 --> 00:37:38.500
Awash in novel sights
and sounds,

00:37:38.500 --> 00:37:40.500
babies must begin to learn

00:37:40.500 --> 00:37:43.830
how to navigate
a roiling sea of sensations.

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:49.300
WOMAN:
There's a huge task
in organizing the world

00:37:49.300 --> 00:37:53.160
that must be difficult,
but the babies seem to do it.

00:37:53.160 --> 00:37:55.930
They act like little scientists.

00:37:55.930 --> 00:38:01.360
They actively explore and
construct a view of the world

00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:03.860
and in that sense,
they are parallel

00:38:03.860 --> 00:38:07.300
to what we as scientists, uh,
do our entire lives

00:38:07.300 --> 00:38:09.130
and what, uh, all of us do

00:38:09.130 --> 00:38:12.430
as we try to negotiate
a very complicated world

00:38:12.430 --> 00:38:14.660
that's constantly under change.

00:38:19.500 --> 00:38:22.830
NARRATOR:
Babies are
exquisitely sensitive.

00:38:25.700 --> 00:38:29.330
A newborn can identify
his mother's whispered coos,

00:38:29.330 --> 00:38:31.860
respond to the fragrance
of her body

00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:34.230
and the sweet taste
of her milk...

00:38:37.200 --> 00:38:40.630
Even recognize her face.

00:38:40.630 --> 00:38:44.600
WOMAN:
When you're holding your baby
and rocking him in your arms

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:46.130
and peering down at him,

00:38:46.130 --> 00:38:48.930
your face happens
to be the distance

00:38:48.930 --> 00:38:52.100
that babies like
to look at most of all.

00:38:52.100 --> 00:38:55.860
And in fact,
even by two days of age,

00:38:55.860 --> 00:39:01.830
a newborn baby can recognize
his mother from sight alone.

00:39:01.830 --> 00:39:04.230
Now, that's quite
a remarkable ability

00:39:04.230 --> 00:39:06.930
for a baby that has
a poorly developed eye

00:39:06.930 --> 00:39:10.100
and for a baby that has
a poorly developed brain.

00:39:10.100 --> 00:39:13.600
(<i> cooing</i> )

00:39:13.600 --> 00:39:16.530
NARRATOR:
Vision is the last
of the senses to develop.

00:39:16.530 --> 00:39:18.300
(<i> cooing</i> )

00:39:18.300 --> 00:39:21.560
With an immature eye
sending wobbly signals

00:39:21.560 --> 00:39:25.000
to a still developing brain,
it's no surprise

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:29.360
that a baby looks out on
a different world than an adult.

00:39:34.600 --> 00:39:37.100
LEWIS:
What the baby is seeing then,

00:39:37.100 --> 00:39:40.530
we think looks something
like a faded photograph.

00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:41.930
If you take a photograph

00:39:41.930 --> 00:39:44.900
and sort of fade it out
so that it's all washed out

00:39:44.900 --> 00:39:48.430
and if you're looking at the
faded photograph through a tube,

00:39:48.430 --> 00:39:50.930
then that is what
the world would look like

00:39:50.930 --> 00:39:52.600
to a newborn baby.

00:39:54.260 --> 00:39:57.500
The fact that the baby
doesn't see very well

00:39:57.500 --> 00:40:00.800
in a sense is very good
for an immature brain

00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:03.600
and that's because
this immature brain

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:06.030
cannot handle
excess stimulation.

00:40:06.030 --> 00:40:07.730
So what the eye is doing

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:10.830
is dampening down
that external stimulation,

00:40:10.830 --> 00:40:14.960
making it something that the
brain can handle much better.

00:40:14.960 --> 00:40:17.430
But it's also important
to remember

00:40:17.430 --> 00:40:21.160
that no matter how dampened down
that stimulation is

00:40:21.160 --> 00:40:24.230
that's going into
this very immature brain,

00:40:24.230 --> 00:40:26.360
that stimulation is critical.

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:33.260
NARRATOR:
What happens
if the brain doesn't get

00:40:33.260 --> 00:40:35.030
the stimulation it needs?

00:40:35.030 --> 00:40:37.200
What if light falls
upon the eye

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:39.530
but never reaches
its destination?

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:43.260
Holly McMillan
is just five weeks old.

00:40:43.260 --> 00:40:45.060
A healthy, normal baby.

00:40:45.060 --> 00:40:48.700
But her right eye
is clouded by a faulty lens--

00:40:48.700 --> 00:40:51.560
a cataract
that must be removed at once

00:40:51.560 --> 00:40:54.700
or she will never see
like a normal child.

00:40:59.630 --> 00:41:01.900
WOMAN:
On the day that she was born,

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:04.430
we noticed that her eye--
her right eye--

00:41:04.430 --> 00:41:06.930
didn't open as wide
as, uh, her left eye.

00:41:06.930 --> 00:41:08.730
But in my family,

00:41:08.730 --> 00:41:11.030
I have a sister and my father
that have an eye

00:41:11.030 --> 00:41:13.400
that's a little bit--
just a little bit smaller

00:41:13.400 --> 00:41:16.300
than the other, so we didn't
really think anything of it.

00:41:16.300 --> 00:41:17.800
But we were informed

00:41:17.800 --> 00:41:21.600
that we would have to have
surgery to remove the lens.

00:41:21.600 --> 00:41:25.830
From what we hear, the sooner
the better for the surgery,

00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:28.160
so hopefully it's soon enough.

00:41:31.130 --> 00:41:33.130
Basically this is...
after all our discussions

00:41:33.130 --> 00:41:35.130
that we had before,
this is the final form

00:41:35.130 --> 00:41:37.030
that just gives
me permission
to go ahead

00:41:37.030 --> 00:41:38.530
and do the right eye,
all right?

00:41:38.530 --> 00:41:39.700
Mm-hmm.

00:41:39.700 --> 00:41:41.800
That way
I won't forget.

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:45.960
MAN:
For a baby, it's really urgent
that we get in there

00:41:45.960 --> 00:41:48.600
because if a baby
has a cataract, uh,

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:51.960
the images that are supposed
to be getting in--

00:41:51.960 --> 00:41:53.600
those images which are critical

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:56.100
for the brain to be able
to develop its vision--

00:41:56.100 --> 00:41:58.030
uh, those images
aren't getting there

00:41:58.030 --> 00:42:01.100
and as a result, the brain
is not getting the opportunity

00:42:01.100 --> 00:42:02.430
to experience vision

00:42:02.430 --> 00:42:04.630
and go through its normal
visual development

00:42:04.630 --> 00:42:06.400
which allows it
to eventually create

00:42:06.400 --> 00:42:08.630
the healthy, normal vision
that we all know.

00:42:08.630 --> 00:42:10.330
When Grandma has a cataract,

00:42:10.330 --> 00:42:13.500
all of her connections
between eye and brain

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:15.460
have been formed years ago

00:42:15.460 --> 00:42:17.930
and they remain stable
over time

00:42:17.930 --> 00:42:21.700
so even if they're not used,
they don't go away.

00:42:21.700 --> 00:42:24.260
But when your child
has a cataract,

00:42:24.260 --> 00:42:26.100
it's the "use it or lose it"
game

00:42:26.100 --> 00:42:28.300
that's being played
during development.

00:42:28.300 --> 00:42:30.430
It's still a period
of decision-making

00:42:30.430 --> 00:42:32.000
and pruning of connections.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:35.030
In fact, even just one
or two months

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:38.360
of missing visual experience
from birth

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:42.900
can have permanent consequences
on the way that brain

00:42:42.900 --> 00:42:47.260
is wired up and on what
that brain can do later on.

00:42:54.530 --> 00:42:56.060
She'll do fine.

00:43:01.860 --> 00:43:03.760
Okay, cutie pie.

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:06.000
Thank you.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:08.000
All right, you'll see
her soon, okay?

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:09.000
Okay, thanks.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.160
We'll take good care
of her.

00:43:25.100 --> 00:43:28.100
(<i> monitors beeping</i> )

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:40.930
LEVIN:
Okay, so there's the cataract
right there inside the eye.

00:43:40.930 --> 00:43:44.060
(<i> monitors beeping</i> )

00:43:44.060 --> 00:43:46.130
I've just got a little bit
of a piece left here

00:43:46.130 --> 00:43:47.330
that I need to get rid of.

00:43:50.900 --> 00:43:52.260
Thank you.

00:44:01.230 --> 00:44:03.800
She's still
sound asleep.

00:44:07.560 --> 00:44:10.900
MOTHER:
Oh, what
a sweetie.

00:44:16.900 --> 00:44:18.660
Now we're just going
to slip this in.

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:21.600
In the old days,
we used to do this under
general anesthesia,

00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:23.230
but the nice thing
about this lens

00:44:23.230 --> 00:44:24.960
is it allows us
to do it this way.

00:44:24.960 --> 00:44:28.360
NARRATOR:
Within a week of the operation,
Holly's eye has healed

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:31.300
and Dr. Levin inserts
a contact lens

00:44:31.300 --> 00:44:35.160
which Holly will need
for the rest of her life.

00:44:35.160 --> 00:44:36.660
For the first time,

00:44:36.660 --> 00:44:40.600
Holly's right eye is sending
clear images to her brain.

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:44.160
The key is if you just put
your hand right underneath

00:44:44.160 --> 00:44:47.930
so you can feel the eyeball
underneath, you'll be fine.

00:44:47.930 --> 00:44:50.730
All of a sudden it's as if
the eye was open to the brain.

00:44:50.730 --> 00:44:52.560
It's the same
as if the baby came out

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:53.960
of that dark, jet-black womb

00:44:53.960 --> 00:44:55.800
and all of a sudden
opened their eyes

00:44:55.800 --> 00:44:57.260
in a delivery room somewhere.

00:44:59.500 --> 00:45:03.630
NARRATOR:
But Holly's vision
is still in danger.

00:45:03.630 --> 00:45:05.160
For at least five years,

00:45:05.160 --> 00:45:07.360
until her visual development
stabilizes,

00:45:07.360 --> 00:45:10.400
she will have to wear a patch
for most of her waking hours

00:45:10.400 --> 00:45:12.130
over her good left eye,

00:45:12.130 --> 00:45:14.030
or else her brain
will never learn

00:45:14.030 --> 00:45:15.660
to use the right eye to see.

00:45:15.660 --> 00:45:17.360
LEWIS:
If the good eye was not patched,

00:45:17.360 --> 00:45:20.200
there is no point
in having the surgery at all.

00:45:20.200 --> 00:45:22.800
There's no point
in having the contact lens.

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:24.130
You have this weak eye

00:45:24.130 --> 00:45:27.030
that has to fight
for cortical connections

00:45:27.030 --> 00:45:30.260
with a totally normal,
strong, good eye.

00:45:30.260 --> 00:45:33.730
And that totally normal,
strong, good eye, if allowed,

00:45:33.730 --> 00:45:36.060
will take over
all the brain space,

00:45:36.060 --> 00:45:38.100
leave nothing
for the deprived eye,

00:45:38.100 --> 00:45:41.000
and the deprived eye
will get weaker and weaker.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:42.960
Sounds a little
counterintuitive.

00:45:42.960 --> 00:45:45.930
Patching the good eye
should cause the same problem

00:45:45.930 --> 00:45:47.400
that the cataract did.

00:45:47.400 --> 00:45:48.700
But, in fact, it doesn't,

00:45:48.700 --> 00:45:51.060
and we really don't understand
why that is.

00:45:51.060 --> 00:45:53.960
And you can patch
that good eye intensely

00:45:53.960 --> 00:45:57.430
and virtually never see
any adverse effect of that.

00:45:57.430 --> 00:45:59.100
That's one of our mysteries.

00:45:59.100 --> 00:46:01.960
LEWIS:
Now, Daddy, if you'll
just shut your eyes

00:46:01.960 --> 00:46:05.300
as I show you
each one of these cards.

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:07.330
NARRATOR:
Holly's cataract
has been removed.

00:46:07.330 --> 00:46:08.930
(<i> whistles</i> )

00:46:08.930 --> 00:46:11.260
NARRATOR:
But how well can Holly see?

00:46:11.260 --> 00:46:14.030
Okay, we got
one beautiful look
over there.

00:46:14.030 --> 00:46:18.000
NARRATOR:
Just minutes after Holly
receives her contact lens,

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:20.700
psychologist Terri Lewis
examines her vision

00:46:20.700 --> 00:46:24.330
by watching whether a finely
calibrated series of patterns

00:46:24.330 --> 00:46:25.830
captures her attention.

00:46:25.830 --> 00:46:28.630
You can't
play the game with
your eyes closed.

00:46:28.630 --> 00:46:31.100
No, you can't.

00:46:31.100 --> 00:46:33.500
LEWIS:
We find that even
within ten minutes

00:46:33.500 --> 00:46:35.560
of first being able to see...

00:46:35.560 --> 00:46:37.060
(<i> whistles</i> )

00:46:37.060 --> 00:46:40.030
the baby can see
as well as a normal newborn.

00:46:40.030 --> 00:46:44.630
That tells us that the brain
can mature up to some point

00:46:44.630 --> 00:46:46.600
without any visual experience--

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:48.060
up to the newborn levels,

00:46:48.060 --> 00:46:50.130
because certainly,
there's no visual experience

00:46:50.130 --> 00:46:51.700
while the baby's in utero.

00:46:51.700 --> 00:46:54.560
NARRATOR:
Although cataract babies
like Holly

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:56.130
see as well as newborn babies,

00:46:56.130 --> 00:46:59.200
they don't see as well
as babies their own age.

00:46:59.200 --> 00:47:01.160
(<i> whistles</i> ):
Here we go, Holly.

00:47:01.160 --> 00:47:03.330
NARRATOR:
But they catch up quickly.

00:47:03.330 --> 00:47:05.460
LEWIS:
It's shocking
how quickly vision improves

00:47:05.460 --> 00:47:08.830
after that contact lens
is put in.

00:47:08.830 --> 00:47:11.030
We found that within one hour,

00:47:11.030 --> 00:47:13.130
we have
a significant improvement

00:47:13.130 --> 00:47:16.730
in how well the babies can see.

00:47:16.730 --> 00:47:19.960
Now, why this is so exciting is
because it tells us

00:47:19.960 --> 00:47:22.600
that although the brain
is no better

00:47:22.600 --> 00:47:24.460
than that of a normal newborn

00:47:24.460 --> 00:47:27.600
in the absence
of visual experience,

00:47:27.600 --> 00:47:29.900
once it gets
that visual experience,

00:47:29.900 --> 00:47:31.500
it's ready to go.

00:47:31.500 --> 00:47:34.560
It's champing at the bit,
because that first little bit,

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:37.530
even that first hour
of visual experience,

00:47:37.530 --> 00:47:41.200
is going to send
that brain into action faster

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:43.500
than it would
in normal development.

00:47:52.700 --> 00:47:55.460
NARRATOR:
In a series of carefully
controlled studies

00:47:55.460 --> 00:47:58.160
comparing normal babies
to cataract babies,

00:47:58.160 --> 00:48:01.560
Lewis has found that,
as cataract babies grow,

00:48:01.560 --> 00:48:03.200
their vision continues
to improve

00:48:03.200 --> 00:48:05.700
until they reach
their first birthday.

00:48:13.660 --> 00:48:18.260
LEWIS:
The children do begin
falling behind after a year,

00:48:18.260 --> 00:48:20.560
but, on average,
with early treatment

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:23.130
and complying
with doctor's instructions,

00:48:23.130 --> 00:48:27.800
the eye can end up being
a totally good, functioning eye.

00:48:27.800 --> 00:48:29.200
(<i> giggles</i> )

00:48:39.860 --> 00:48:43.400
NARRATOR:
It has been seven months
since Holly's surgery,

00:48:43.400 --> 00:48:45.330
and her parents have been
diligently patching

00:48:45.330 --> 00:48:47.960
her good eye.

00:48:47.960 --> 00:48:51.130
(<i> Holly cooing</i> )

